\begin_layout Chapter
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of the “Electric Arc Simulation” Seminar is to offer the students
 an overview regarding the field of electric arc simulation.
 The general term of Electric Arc Simulation can define a plenitude of mathemati
cal models that have been developed over the years in order to understand,
 build and improve the arc extinguishing process in switching devices.
 The arc mathematical models can be separated in two main categories according
 to their main purpose: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- “Black-box” (sometimes refereed as Conductance models): where the electric
 arc is regarded as an network element and its interaction with the electrical
 network is analyzed; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Physical Models: that regard in detail the physic of the discharge and
 the interaction between different physical factors that play a role in
 the arc maintenance or extinguishing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the first type of simulation models, well-known are the models developed
 by Cassie 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Cas39"

\end_inset

 and Mayr 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "May43b"

\end_inset

.
 These models have simple physical assumptions and offer simple mathematical
 representations, using fitting parameters, of the complex discharge phenomena
 taking place into a switching device.
 Their purpose is to recreate the voltage-current arc characteristics that
 can be further used in a network analysis.
 This is a very important point for electric devices developers as well
 as for the electric network developers because by means of this models
 the over-current and over-voltage that can stress the electrical can be
 approximated.
 Some authors use in their mathematical formulation certain physical arc
 parameters in order to improve the originally constant parameters (e.g.
 arc power losses) but still the real arc physics is nowhere near described
 by these equations.
 In order to recreate the physics of an arc discharge the second type of
 models are always used.
 These models are based on the fluid-dynamic conservation laws, e.g.
 Navier-Stockes equations, coupled with the Maxwell equations used to describe
 the electromagnetic effects produced by the electric current.
 Due to their mathematical formulation and complexity, these models are
 not used up to the present in conjunction with network analysis software
 and their main purpose resides only into giving a good representation of
 the arc formation, movement and extinguishing into a circuit breaker.
 
\end_layout

