\begin_layout Chapter
Mathematics of the “Black-box” models 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the electric point of view, the “Black-box” models regard the arc as
 a two-pole nonlinear resistive element.
 This behavior is represented by the Voltage-Current characteristic of the
 arc that offers a macroscopic description of the switching process taking
 place inside the switching device.
 All the models studied here are represented by an Ordinary Differential
 Equation (ODE) and are based on the simple models developed by Mayr and
 Cassie.
 Both of these ground models consider as a state variable for the differential
 equation the electric arc conductance and for this reason in some books
 they can be found under the name of Conductance Models.
 The theoretical description of the two main models, that are also the most
 basic ones, will be given in the following points.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
General assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mathematical description of both researchers is based on a series of
 simple physical assumptions based on 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Energy Balance Equation"

\end_inset

.
 The equation states that the power brought into the electric arc equals
 the power losses from the arc plus a certain amount of power that is stored
 into the arc column.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{IN}=P_{OUT}+P_{STORED}\label{eq:Energy Balance Equation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The input power represents, in this case, the product between the network
 voltage and the current flowing through the arc (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{IN}=u\, i$
\end_inset

), while the power stored in the arc column can be seen as an energy change
 over time (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{STORED}=dQ/dt$
\end_inset

).
 Further, it may be assumed that the stored energy produces a change in
 the arc physical parameters (e.g.
 electric conductivity).
 This leads to a change in the arc conductance as a function of the arc
 stored energy:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G=G(Q)=G\left(\int(P_{IN}-P_{OUT})dt\right)\label{eq:Arc conductance as function of stored energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By deriving 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Arc conductance as function of stored energy"

\end_inset

 with respect to time and multiplying by 
\begin_inset Formula $1/G$
\end_inset

 we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{G}\frac{dG}{dt}=\frac{1}{G}\frac{dG(Q)}{dt}=\frac{1}{G}\frac{dG}{dQ}\frac{dQ}{dt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{G}\frac{dG}{dt}=\frac{1}{G}\frac{dG}{dQ}\left(P_{IN}-P_{OUT}\right)\label{eq:Energy Balance as function of Arc Conductance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Energy Balance as function of Arc Conductance"

\end_inset

 describes the arc energy balance through a differential equation that considers
: the energy input, output and the changes brought by the stored energy
 on the arc electrical conductance over time.
 This equation represents the ground form of the all 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Black-Box
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 models and depending how the terms in this equation are considered different
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Black-Box
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 models were developed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Description of the Cassie arc model 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to create a mathematical description of the switching process,
 Cassie assumed that the
\shape italic
 energy losses
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $(P_{OUT}$
\end_inset

) 
\shape italic
are done entirely by
\shape default
 
\shape italic
convection 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\shape italic
(insert figure with convection )
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\shape default
Indirectly,
\shape italic
 
\shape default
this assumption implies that up to the power sink location, e.g.
 the arc surface, there is a constant heat distribution produced by the
 power input 
\begin_inset Formula $(P_{IN}$
\end_inset

).
 As follows, the temperature distribution, current distribution and arc
 parameters are constant and the following equation is verified:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G=f(Q)=ct\label{eq:Cassie Assumption}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By replacing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Cassie Assumption"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Energy Balance as function of Arc Conductance"

\end_inset

 and considering 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{IN}=u^{2}G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{OUT}=u_{a}^{2}G$
\end_inset

, the following equation is obtained: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{G}\frac{dG}{dt}=\frac{1}{G}\frac{G}{Q}(u^{2}G-u_{a}^{2}G)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{G}\frac{dG}{dt}=\frac{G}{Q}u_{a}^{2}\left(\frac{u^{2}}{u_{a}^{2}}-1\right)=\frac{G}{Q}\frac{P_{OUT}}{G}\left(\frac{u^{2}}{u_{a}^{2}}-1\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{G}\frac{dG}{dt}=\frac{1}{\tau_{a}}\left(\frac{u^{2}}{u_{a}^{2}}-1\right)\label{eq:CassieEq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=Q/P_{OUT}$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Description of the Mayr arc model 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Mayr model the electric arc is regarded as having a cylindrical column
 with a constant diameter.
 In this model 
\shape italic
the energy losses 
\shape default

\begin_inset Formula $(P_{OUT}$
\end_inset

) 
\shape italic
are considered to be only due to thermal conduction effects
\shape default
.
 By using this approximation the author implies that the temperature distributio
n inside the arc column is not constant and follows a distribution given
 by the amount of energy input (
\begin_inset Formula $T=f(Q)$
\end_inset

).
 The temperature distribution will have as a consequence a change in the
 plasma physical properties (e.g.
 electrical conductivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, the resulting arc conductance will be a function of the energy input
 given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConductivityEq"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G=Ke^{^{(Q/Q_{0})}}\label{eq:ConductivityEq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 are constants.
 By replacing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConductivityEq"

\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Energy Balance as function of Arc Conductance"

\end_inset

 and after a few rearrangements the final form of the Mayr differential
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MayrEq"

\end_inset

 for the electric arc will be obtained: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d\, lnG}{dt}=\frac{1}{\tau}\left(\frac{u_{a}i}{P_{0}}-1\right)\label{eq:MayrEq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=Q_{0}/P_{\text{0}}$
\end_inset

 represents the electric arc time constant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this model, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

 are free parameters and must be determined experimentally.
 The simulation model will regard these parameters as input variables.
\end_layout

